title: What will the Norwegian Kroner to one U.S. Dollar daily exchange rate be on 31 October 2017?
preds: Looks like the exchange rate is headed for more volatility over the next several days.  I can't really justify a forecast of 100% for the bin "More than 7.97".  Moderating my forecast.
Based on general news and GJP consensus.
Updating to reflect likely outcomes given weaker (than I expected) position following movement in the currency on 25-26 Oct.
Based on general news and GJP consensus.

Estimate based on this week's range: 7.8875 - 7.9831
A rate increase on 26 Oct looks unlikely so assuming NOK demand will remain relatively stable up to the closing date.

Closed at 7.99 today.
But 8.00 has been a resistance level since late July. YTD trend remains negative. Not convinced it has much upside potential at this point. Forecasts I’m seeing online point to somewhere in the 7.90’s.
Still feel more likely below 7.98.

Norges bank will keep its rate unchanged at its policy meeting on 26 October, since they will likely follow closely the tightening schedule of the ECB. http://www.bis.org/review/r171016e.htm. USD weakness to dominate over next two months, with NOK possibly getting a bump out of the ECB governing council meeting and tapering measures for 2018.
~7.87 on Friday the 13th and headed down.
Based on general news and GJP consensus.
Based on range of values for the last 30 days.
Like the Kroner I'm moving on up.
Norway is doing well the Krone will be quite good thanks to President Trump the Dollar may fall a bit.

Nkroner is a small proxy for oil and Euro economy. Rates in Norway and EU seem near term steady, US rates drifting higher. Little near run political cause for volatile Nkr, so little change by month end. But, push to shove Nkr could rise.

Current rate on October 8th is 8.0030. USD has been appreciating since beginning of September and good economic indicators (e.g. NFP better than expected last Friday) suggest that this is likely to continue.

Norwegian krone holds gains after central bank nudges up rate forecast
https://www.ft.com/content/55bd0878-bd6f-3f8b-8a10-a25ee80319e0 Reading the statement by Norges Bank is like trying to divine the next move by the Federal Reserve's FOMC.

I put together a forecast using 5 years of FRED data. The estimate for the end of the period was about 7.93, so I constructed this distribution around it.  I will probably update based on further qualitative research and certainly after new data becomes available.

USD positioning is very short - even if NOK strengthens - the USD leg should strengthen. Also USDNOK is above 7.97 now so if we assume spot is well priced then don't see how it can be more than 50% chance it's lower than 2bf below.

This remains volatile because the ranges are tiny, less than 2% fluctuation sends you from one option to the next. We're at 7.96 now, and a 2% fluctuation downwards sends you to 7.8, another 2% and you're at 7.64...

Selected currency forecasts call for the NOK to continue to drop in value relative to the USD, with the NOK reaching a low around 7.5 by September 2018.  Looking at the 5YR trend and currency rate of change indicators, I anticipate that the NOK will hit 7.8 by 31 October 2017.
Longer term is 8.0+.  US has decent chance of raising interest rates, too.
Literally just plugged in a normal distribution assuming mean of today's spot (7.78) and a 1-month standard deviation of 2.8% based on realized returns.
Stable economies both in US and Norway. Plateau reached

NOK/USD is currently at 7.8.  I'm expecting the USDX trend to either continue its downward move with the German election results and an uneventful Spanish referendum or to change directions with either a more eventful Spanish referendum and continued tax hunting in Europe.
USDNOK on an appreciation trend as growth recovers, central bank brings rate hike projections forward and oil prices recover.
Revising based upon normal distrubtion with updated data

The value on 10/31 depends hugely on Norway's rate decision on 10/26. I think persistently low energy prices will push it back up to around 8 unless Norway raises rates.  They probably won't do that though, so they can stay in parity with SEK. http://www.xe.com/currencyconverter/convert/?Amount=1&From=NOK&To=SEK
This is roughly based upon a normal distribution of the prices over the last 35 days.
Decreasing and increasing around October/November in the last decade
7.84 on Friday 15 September.  Will dollar continue to weaken?  Yes.  Will oil prices stay steady or trend up?  Yes.  Kroner will strengthen.
Based on general news and GJP consensus.

As of 9/17, spot is 7.844.
For trailing 6 weeks, high is 7.96, low is 7.73.
Because Kroner is correlated with oil price and oil appears to be traveling higher, I put more weight on 7.83 to 7.97. To improve in future, could look at option implied probability move ( where to get liquid currency option prices?? ) or just a better trailing N month volatility measure.

Noway's economic fundamentals are good, but the K has already had a pretty significant appreciation. I think it has risen to the point that the Norwegians will start trying to keep the value stable to prevent any big hit to exports and the markets will also see some profit taking. But these are tight bands, and I'm really just guessing.

Economic news from Norway are pretty good, Us is more in an "as usual not bad not so good" economic trend. => increase Kroner value
Until end of October, the US may still suffer from tornadoes and hurricanes (hurricane season ends after October) and Norway will probably not suffer from extreme climate even but snowfall, extremely frequent. => may decrease $US value
Today's rate is $1 per 7.88 Kroner
"More than 7.97" seems unlikely
"7.83-7.97" may not be exclude
"7.72-7.83" if current dynamic ceases
"7.528-7.72" in a "business as usual" trend (aim around 7.6)
"less than 7.58" if something goes wrong for the US but not Norway

The voters in Norway elected a right-center populist government on September 12.  The currency gained value against the US dollar during the campaigns with slight inflation following the elections.  Institutional currency traders will maintain their position with the krone.  A nationalist Norway seems like it will have a healthy economy and its currency will hold steady.

futures (http://www.cmegroup.com/trading/fx/g10/norwegian-krone.html) have it roughly between 1/.13 and 1/.1227 (approx 7.7 and 8.2 ) with an average of about 7.9. 
Since the ranges given in the question are pretty small (1-2 per cent of the value) there is a lot of uncertainty here. 
Since the trend has been up over the last couple of days, I'm assigning a little more to up than down...
I think the Kronar continues to strengthen against the dollar over the next two months as long as oil prices don't fall and economic fundamentals don't shift in that time.

Economic news is not good in Norway, exchange rate on short and long term is dropping. Projection of current drop gradient implies something in the 7.5 range by the end of October, distributing around that target with some minimal chance of the course stabilizing about the current position. No chance of higher rate.
